# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: terminfo-termcap
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Early character encodings that originated with optical or electrical telegraphy and in early computers could only represent a subset of the characters used in languages, sometimes restricted to upper case letters, numerals and limited punctuation.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Over time, encodings capable of representing more characters were created, such as ASCII, ISO/IEC 8859, and Unicode encodings such as UTF-8 and UTF-16.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The most popular character encoding on the World Wide Web is UTF-8, which is used in 98.9% of surveyed web sites, as of January 2026.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] In application programs and operating system tasks, both UTF-8 and UTF-16 are popular options.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The history of character codes illustrates the evolving need for machine-mediated character-based symbolic information over a distance, using once-novel electrical means.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The earliest codes were based upon manual and hand-written encoding and cyphering systems, such as Bacon's cipher, Braille, international maritime signal flags, and the 4-digit encoding of Chinese characters for a Chinese telegraph code (Hans Schjellerup, 1869).
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] With the adoption of electrical and electro-mechanical techniques these earliest codes were adapted to the new capabilities and limitations of the early machines.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The earliest well-known electrically transmitted character code, Morse code, introduced in the 1840s, used a system of four "symbols" (short signal, long signal, short space, long space) to generate codes of variable length.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Though some commercial use of Morse code was via machinery, it was often used as a manual code, generated by hand on a telegraph key and decipherable by ear, and persists in amateur radio and aeronautical use.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Most codes are of fixed per-character length or variable-length sequences of fixed-length codes (e.g.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Common examples of character encoding systems include Morse code, the Baudot code, the American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII) and Unicode.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Unicode, a well-defined and extensible encoding system, has replaced most earlier character encodings, but the path of code development to the present is fairly well known.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The Baudot code, a five-bit encoding, was created by Émile Baudot in 1870, patented in 1874, modified by Donald Murray in 1901, and standardized by CCITT as International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The name *baudot* has been erroneously applied to ITA2 and its many variants.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] ITA2 suffered from many shortcomings and was often improved by many equipment manufacturers, sometimes creating compatibility issues.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Herman Hollerith invented punch card data encoding in the late 19th century to analyze census data.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Initially, each hole position represented a different data element, but later, numeric information was encoded by numbering the lower rows 0 to 9, with a punch in a column representing its row number.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Later alphabetic data was encoded by allowing more than one punch per column.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Electromechanical tabulating machines represented date internally by the timing of pulses relative to the motion of the cards through the machine.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] When IBM went to electronic processing, starting with the IBM 603 Electronic Multiplier, it used a variety of binary encoding schemes that were tied to the punch card code.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] IBM used several binary-coded decimal (BCD) six-bit character encoding schemes, starting as early as 1953 in its 702 and 704 computers, and in its later 7000 Series and 1400 series, as well as in associated peripherals.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Since the punched card code then in use was limited to digits, upper-case English letters and a few special characters, six bits were sufficient.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] These BCD encodings extended existing simple four-bit numeric encoding to include alphabetic and special characters, mapping them easily to punch-card encoding which was already in widespread use.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] IBM's codes were used primarily with IBM equipment.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Other computer vendors of the era had their own character codes, often six-bit, such as the encoding used by the UNIVAC I.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] They usually had the ability to read tapes produced on IBM equipment.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] IBM's BCD encodings were the precursors of their Extended Binary-Coded Decimal Interchange Code (usually abbreviated as EBCDIC), an eight-bit encoding scheme developed in 1963 for the IBM System/360 that featured a larger character set, including lower case letters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] In 1959, the U.S. military defined its Fieldata code, a six-or seven-bit code, introduced by the U.S.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] While Fieldata addressed many of the then-modern issues (e.g. letter and digit codes arranged for machine collation), it fell short of its goals and was short-lived.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] In 1963 the first ASCII code was released (X3.4-1963) by the ASCII committee (which contained at least one member of the Fieldata committee, W.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Leubbert), which addressed most of the shortcomings of Fieldata, using a simpler seven-bit code.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Many of the changes were subtle, such as collatable character sets within certain numeric ranges.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] ASCII63 was a success, widely adopted by industry, and with the follow-up issue of the 1967 ASCII code (which added lower-case letters and fixed some "control code" issues) ASCII67 was adopted fairly widely.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] ASCII67's American-centric nature was somewhat addressed in the European ECMA-6 standard.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Eight-bit extended ASCII encodings, such as various vendor extensions and the ISO/IEC 8859 series, supported all ASCII characters as well as additional non-ASCII characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] In 1985, the average personal computer user's hard disk drive could store only about 10 megabytes, and it cost approximately US$250 on the wholesale market (and much higher if purchased separately at retail), so it was very important at the time to make every bit count.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The compromise solution that was eventually found and developed into Unicode was to break the assumption (dating back to telegraph codes) that each character should always directly correspond to a particular sequence of bits.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Instead, characters would first be mapped to a universal intermediate representation in the form of abstract numbers called code points.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Code points would then be represented in a variety of ways and with various default numbers of bits per character (code units) depending on context.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] To encode code points higher than the length of the code unit, such as above 256 for eight-bit units, the solution was to implement variable-length encodings where an escape sequence would signal that subsequent bits should be parsed as a higher code point.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The various terms related to character encoding are often used inconsistently or incorrectly.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Historically, the same standard would specify a repertoire of characters and how they were to be encoded into a stream of code units – usually with a single character per code unit.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] However, due to the emergence of more sophisticated character encodings, the distinction between terms has become important.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] A character is the smallest unit of text that has semantic value.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] In linguistics, this is called a grapheme and each of the various ways it may be written are called glyphs.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] What constitutes a character varies between character encodings.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] For example, for letters with diacritics, there are two distinct approaches that can be taken to encode them.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] They can be encoded either as a single unified character (known as a precomposed character), or as separate characters that combine into a single glyph.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The former simplifies the text handling system, but the latter allows any letter/diacritic combination to be used in text.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Some writing systems, such as Arabic and Hebrew, have graphemes whose shape and joining depend on context.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] A character set is a collection of characters used to represent text.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] For example, the Latin alphabet and Greek alphabet are character sets.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] A coded character set is a character set with each item uniquely mapped to a numberic value.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] This is also known as a code page, although that term is generally antiquated.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Originally, *code page* referred to a page number in an IBM manual that defined a particular character encoding.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Other vendors, including Microsoft, SAP, and Oracle Corporation, also published their own code pages, including notable Windows code page and code page 437.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Despite no longer referring to specific pages in a manual, many character encodings are still identified to by the same number.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Likewise, the term *code page* is still used to refer to character encoding.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the term *charmap* is commonly used; usually in the larger context of locales.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] IBM's Character Data Representation Architecture (CDRA) designates each entity with a coded character set identifier (CCSID), which is variously called a *charset*, *character set*, *code page*, or *CHARMAP*.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] A character repertoire is a set of characters that can be represented by a particular coded character set.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The repertoire may be closed, meaning that no additions are allowed without creating a new standard (as is the case with ASCII and most of the ISO-8859 series); or it may be open, allowing additions (as is the case with Unicode and to a limited extent Windows code pages).
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] A code point is the value or position of a character in a coded character set.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] A code point is represented by a sequence of code units.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Code space is the range of numerical values spanned by a coded character set.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] A code unit is the minimum bit combination that can represent a character in a character encoding (in computer science terms, it is the word size of the character encoding).
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Common code units include 7-bit, 8-bit, 16-bit, and 32-bit.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] In some encodings, some characters are encoded as multiple code units.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Unicode and its parallel standard, the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set, together constitute a unified standard for character encoding.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The purpose of this decomposition is to establish a universal set of characters that can be encoded in a variety of ways.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] To describe the model precisely, Unicode uses existing terms and defines new terms.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] An abstract character repertoire (ACR) is the full set of abstract characters that a system supports.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Unicode has an open repertoire, meaning that new characters will be added to the repertoire over time.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] A coded character set (CCS) is a function that maps characters to *code points* (each code point represents one character).
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] For example, in a given repertoire, the capital letter "A" in the Latin alphabet might be represented by the code point 65, the character "B" by 66, and so on.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Multiple coded character sets may share the same character repertoire; for example ISO/IEC 8859-1 and IBM code pages 037 and 500 all cover the same repertoire but map them to different code points.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Hardware and software systems typically have a maximum "native" word length, such as 16 or 32 bits.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] A character encoding may define code points whose length exceeds a system's native word length.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] *A character encoding form* (CEF) is the mapping of code points to *code units* that break up a code point in a standardized way so that each code unit fits within the system's word length.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] For example, a computer that represents numbers in 16-bit units can only represent code points up to 65,535 per unit, but larger code points can be represented using multiple 16-bit units as defined by the CEF.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] A character encoding scheme (CES) is the mapping of code units to a sequence of octets to facilitate storage on an octet-based file system or transmission over an octet-based network.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] See comparison of Unicode encodings for a detailed discussion.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] There may be a higher-level protocol which supplies additional information to select the particular variant of a Unicode character, particularly where there are regional variants that have been 'unified' in Unicode as the same character.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] An example is the XML attribute xml:lang.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The Unicode model uses the term "character map" for other systems which directly assign a sequence of characters to a sequence of bytes, covering all of the CCS, CEF and CES layers.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] A character is commonly documented as 'U+' followed by its code point value in hexadecimal.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The range of valid code points (the code space) for the Unicode standard is U+0000 to U+10FFFF, inclusive, divided in 17 planes, identified by the numbers 0 to 16.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Characters in the range U+0000 to U+FFFF are in plane 0, called the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP).
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] This plane contains the most commonly used characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Characters in the range U+10000 to U+10FFFF in the other planes are called supplementary characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Consider, "ab̲c𐐀" – a string containing a Unicode combining character (U+0332 ◌̲ COMBINING LOW LINE to underline the ⟨b⟩) as well as a supplementary character (U+10400 𐐀 DESERET CAPITAL LETTER LONG I).
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Note in particular that 𐐀 is represented with either one 32-bit value (UTF-32), two 16-bit values (UTF-16), or four 8-bit values (UTF-8).
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] Although each of those forms uses the same total number of bits (32) to represent the grapheme, it is not obvious how the actual numeric byte values are related.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] To support environments using multiple character encodings, software has been developed to translate text between character encoding schemes, a process known as transcoding.
[src:terminfo-termcap/character-encoding] The most used character encoding on the web is UTF-8, used in 98.9% of surveyed web sites, as of January 2026.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] In computing and telecommunications, a **control character** or **non-printing character** (**NPC**) is a code point in a character set that does not represent a written character or symbol.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] They are used as in-band signaling to cause effects other than the addition of a symbol to the text.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] All other characters are mainly *graphic characters*, also known as *printing characters* (or *printable characters*), except perhaps for "space" characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] In the ASCII standard there are 33 control characters, such as code 7, BEL, which might ring a bell.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Procedural signs in Morse code are a form of control character.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] A form of control characters were introduced in the 1870 Baudot code: NUL and DEL.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The 1901 Murray code added the carriage return (CR) and line feed (LF), and other versions of the Baudot code included other control characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The bell character (BEL), which rang a bell to alert operators, was also an early teletype control character.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Some control characters have also been called "format effectors".
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] There were quite a few control characters defined (33 in ASCII, and ECMA-35 adds 32 more).
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] This was because early terminals had very primitive mechanical or electrical controls that made any kind of state-remembering API quite expensive to implement, thus a different code for each and every function was a requirement.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] All entries in the ASCII table below code 3210 (technically the C0 control code set) are control characters, including CR and LF used to separate lines of text.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The code 12710 (DEL) is also a control character.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Extended ASCII sets defined by ECMA-35 and ISO 8859 added the codes 12810 through 15910 as control characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] This was primarily done so that if the high bit was stripped, it would not change a printing character to a C0 control code.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] IBM's EBCDIC character set contains 65 control codes, including all of the ASCII C0 control codes plus additional codes which were not added to Unicode.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] There were also a number of attempts to define alternative sets of 32 control codes, none of these were transferred to Unicode either.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Control characters may do something when the user inputs them, such as Ctrl+C (End-of-Text character, ETX) to interrupt the running process, and Ctrl+Z (Substitute character, SUB) for ending typed-in file on Windows.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] These uses usually have little to do with their ASCII definition.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Modern systems often describe shortcuts as though they are control characters ("type a Ctrl+V to paste") but the code number is not even used to implement this.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] These 65 control codes were carried over to Unicode.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The Cc control characters have no Name in Unicode, but are given labels such as "<control-001A>" instead.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Unicode added more characters (such as the zero-width non-joiner) that could be considered controls, but it makes a distinction between these "Formatting characters" and the 65 control characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] These are General Category "Cf" instead of "Cc".
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] ASCII-based keyboards have a key labelled "Control", "Ctrl", or (rarely) "Cntl" which is used much like a shift key, being pressed in combination with another letter or symbol key.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] In one implementation, the control key generates the code 64 places below the code for the (generally) uppercase letter it is pressed in combination with (i.e., subtract 0x40 from ASCII code value of the (generally) uppercase letter).
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The other implementation is to take the ASCII code produced by the key and bitwise AND it with 0x1F, forcing bits 5 to 7 to zero.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] For example, pressing "control" and the letter "g" (which is 0110 0111 in binary), produces the code 7 (BELL, 7 in base ten, or 0000 0111 in binary).
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The NULL character (code 0) is represented by Ctrl-@, "@" being the code immediately before "A" in the ASCII character set.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] For convenience, some terminals accept Ctrl-Space as an alias for Ctrl-@.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] In either case, this produces one of the 32 ASCII control codes between 0 and 31.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Neither approach works to produce the DEL character because of its special location in the table and its value (code 12710), Ctrl-? is sometimes used for this character.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] When the control key is held down, letter keys produce the same control characters regardless of the state of the shift or caps lock keys.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] In other words, it does not matter whether the key would have produced an upper-case or a lower-case letter.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The interpretation of the control key with the space, graphics character, and digit keys (ASCII codes 32 to 63) varies between systems.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Some will produce the same character code as if the control key were not held down.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Other systems translate these keys into control characters when the control key is held down.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The interpretation of the control key with non-ASCII ("foreign") keys also varies between systems.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Control characters are often rendered into a printable form known as caret notation by printing a caret (^) and then the ASCII character that has a value of the control character plus 64.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Control characters generated using letter keys are thus displayed with the upper-case form of the letter.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] For example, ^G represents code 7, which is generated by pressing the G key when the control key is held down.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Keyboards also typically have a few single keys which produce control character codes.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] For example, the key labelled "Backspace" typically produces code 8, "Tab" code 9, "Enter" or "Return" code 13 (though some keyboards might produce code 10 for "Enter").
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Many keyboards include keys that do not correspond to any ASCII printable or control character, for example cursor control arrows and word processing functions.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The associated keypresses are communicated to computer programs by one of four methods: appropriating otherwise unused control characters; using some encoding other than ASCII; using multi-character control sequences; or using an additional mechanism outside of generating characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] "Dumb" computer terminals typically use control sequences.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Keyboards attached to stand-alone personal computers made in the 1980s typically use one (or both) of the first two methods.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Modern computer keyboards generate scancodes that identify the specific physical keys that are pressed; computer software then determines how to handle the keys that are pressed, including any of the four methods described above.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The control characters were designed to fall into a few groups: printing and display control, data structuring, transmission control, and miscellaneous.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Printing control characters were first used to control the physical mechanism of printers, the earliest output device.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] An early example of this idea was the use of Figures (FIGS) and Letters (LTRS) in Baudot code to shift between two code pages.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] A later, but still early, example was the out-of-band ASA carriage control characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Later, control characters were integrated into the stream of data to be printed.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The carriage return character (CR), when sent to such a device, causes it to put the character at the edge of the paper at which writing begins (it may, or may not, also move the printing position to the next line).
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The line feed character (LF/NL) causes the device to put the printing position on the next line.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The vertical and horizontal tab characters (VT and HT/TAB) cause the output device to move the printing position to the next tab stop in the direction of reading.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The form feed character (FF/NP) starts a new sheet of paper, and may or may not move to the start of the first line.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The backspace character (BS) moves the printing position one character space backwards.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] On printers, including hard-copy terminals, this is most often used so the printer can overprint characters to make other, not normally available, characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] On video terminals and other electronic output devices, there are often software (or hardware) configuration choices that allow a destructive backspace (e.g., a BS, SP, BS sequence), which erases, or a non-destructive one, which does not.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The shift in and shift out characters (SI and SO) selected alternate character sets, fonts, underlining, or other printing modes.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Escape sequences were often used to do the same thing.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] With the advent of computer terminals that did not physically print on paper and so offered more flexibility regarding screen placement, erasure, and so forth, printing control codes were adapted.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Form feeds, for example, usually cleared the screen, there being no new paper page to move to.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] More complex escape sequences were developed to take advantage of the flexibility of the new terminals, and indeed of newer printers.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The concept of a control character had always been somewhat limiting, and was extremely so when used with new, much more flexible, hardware.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Control sequences (sometimes implemented as escape sequences) could match the new flexibility and power and became the standard method.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] However, there were, and remain, a large variety of standard sequences to choose from.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The separators (File, Group, Record, and Unit: FS, GS, RS and US) were made to structure data, usually on a tape, in order to simulate punched cards.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] End of medium (EM) warns that the tape (or other recording medium) is ending.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] While many systems use CR/LF and TAB for structuring data, it is possible to encounter the separator control characters in data that needs to be structured.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The separator control characters are not overloaded; there is no general use of them except to separate data into structured groupings.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Their numeric values are contiguous with the space character, which can be considered a member of the group, as a word separator.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] For example, the RS separator is used by RFC 7464 (JSON Text Sequences) to encode a sequence of JSON elements.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Each sequence item starts with a RS character and ends with a line feed.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] This allows to serialize open-ended JSON sequences.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] It is one of the JSON streaming protocols.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The transmission control characters were intended to structure a data stream, and to manage re-transmission or graceful failure, as needed, in the face of transmission errors.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The start of heading (SOH) character was to mark a non-data section of a data stream—the part of a stream containing addresses and other housekeeping data.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The start of text character (STX) marked the end of the header, and the start of the textual part of a stream.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The end of text character (ETX) marked the end of the data of a message.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] A widely used convention is to make the two characters preceding ETX a checksum or CRC for error-detection purposes.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The end of transmission block character (ETB) was used to indicate the end of a block of data, where data was divided into such blocks for transmission purposes.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The escape character (ESC) was intended to "quote" the next character, if it was another control character it would print it instead of performing the control function.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] It is almost never used for this purpose today.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Various printable characters are used as visible "escape characters", depending on context.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The substitute character (SUB) was intended to request a translation of the next character from a printable character to another value, usually by setting bit 5 to zero.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] This is handy because some media (such as sheets of paper produced by typewriters) can transmit only printable characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] However, on MS-DOS systems with files opened in text mode, "end of text" or "end of file" is marked by this Ctrl-Z character, instead of the Ctrl-C or Ctrl-D, which are common on other operating systems.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The cancel character (CAN) signaled that the previous element should be discarded.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The negative acknowledge character (NAK) is a definite flag for, usually, noting that reception was a problem, and, often, that the current element should be sent again.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The acknowledge character (ACK) is normally used as a flag to indicate no problem detected with current element.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] When a transmission medium is half duplex (that is, it can transmit in only one direction at a time), there is usually a master station that can transmit at any time, and one or more slave stations that transmit when they have permission.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The enquire character (ENQ) is generally used by a master station to ask a slave station to send its next message.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] A slave station indicates that it has completed its transmission by sending the end of transmission character (EOT).
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The device control codes (DC1 to DC4) were originally generic, to be implemented as necessary by each device.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] However, a universal need in data transmission is to request the sender to stop transmitting when a receiver is temporarily unable to accept any more data.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Digital Equipment Corporation invented a convention which used 19 (the device control 3 character (DC3), also known as control-S, or XOFF) to "S"top transmission, and 17 (the device control 1 character (DC1), a.k.a. control-Q, or XON) to start transmission.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] It has become so widely used that most don't realize it is not part of official ASCII.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] This technique, however implemented, avoids additional wires in the data cable devoted only to transmission management, which saves money.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] A sensible protocol for the use of such transmission flow control signals must be used, to avoid potential deadlock conditions, however.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] The data link escape character (DLE) was intended to be a signal to the other end of a data link that the following character is a control character such as STX or ETX.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] For example a packet may be structured in the following way (DLE) <STX> <PAYLOAD> (DLE) <ETX>.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Code 7 (BEL) is intended to cause an audible signal in the receiving terminal.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Many of the ASCII control characters were designed for devices of the time that are not often seen today.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] For example, code 22, "synchronous idle" (SYN), was originally sent by synchronous modems (which have to send data constantly) when there was no actual data to send.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] (Modern systems typically use a start bit to announce the beginning of a transmitted word— this is a feature of *asynchronous* communication.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Code 0 (ASCII code name NUL) is a special case.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] In paper tape, it is the case when there are no holes.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] It is convenient to treat this as a *fill* character with no meaning otherwise.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Since the position of a NUL character has no holes punched, it can be replaced with any other character at a later time, so it was typically used to reserve space, either for correcting errors or for inserting information that would be available at a later time or in another place.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] In computing, it is often used for padding in fixed length records; to mark the end of a string; and formerly to give printing devices enough time to execute a control function.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Its 7-bit code is *all-bits-on* in binary, which essentially erased a character cell on a paper tape when overpunched.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Paper tape was a common storage medium when ASCII was developed, with a computing history dating back to WWII code breaking equipment at Biuro Szyfrów.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Paper tape became obsolete in the 1970s, so this aspect of ASCII rarely saw any use after that.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Some systems (such as the original Apple computers) converted it to a backspace.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] But because its code is in the range occupied by other printable characters, and because it had no official assigned glyph, many computer equipment vendors used it as an additional printable character (often an all-black box character useful for erasing text by overprinting with ink).
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Non-erasable programmable ROMs are typically implemented as arrays of fusible elements, each representing a bit, which can only be switched one way, usually from one to zero.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] In such PROMs, the DEL and NUL characters can be used in the same way that they were used on punched tape: one to reserve meaningless fill bytes that can be written later, and the other to convert written bytes to meaningless fill bytes.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] For PROMs that switch one to zero, the roles of NUL and DEL are reversed; also, DEL will only work with 7-bit characters, which are rarely used today; for 8-bit content, the character code 255, commonly defined as a nonbreaking space character, can be used instead of DEL.
[src:terminfo-termcap/control-character] Many file systems do not allow control characters in filenames, as they may have reserved functions.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] In computing, an **escape sequence** is a sequence of characters that has a special semantic meaning based on an established convention that specifies an escape character prefix in addition to the syntax of the rest of the text of a sequence.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] A convention can define any particular character code as a sequence prefix.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Some conventions use a normal, printable character such as backslash (\) or ampersand (&).
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Others use a non-printable (a.k.a. control) character such as ASCII *escape*.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Escape sequences date back at least to the 1874 Baudot code.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] A common use of an escape sequence is to remove control characters from a data stream so that it does not cause its control function by mistake.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] The control character is replaced with an escape character and one or more other subsequent characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] After escaping the normal context in which the control character would have caused an action, the sequence is replaced by the removed character.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] To transmit the escape character itself, two copies are sent.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] An escape sequence is often used in character and string literals, to express characters that are not printable or clash with the syntax of characters or strings.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] For example, control characters might not be allowed in a source file or may have undesirable side-effects if typed into a command.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] A feature of C and many programming languages influenced by it is that the beginning of an escape sequence in such text literals is marked by a backslash (`\`).
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Common examples of these C-style escape sequences include `\r`, `\n` and `\t` for the carriage return, newline, and tab characters, respectively.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] To account for the fact that using a printable character for escape causes that character to lose its normal meaning, a sequence of two backslash characters (`\\`) is provided to express a single backslash.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] There is also an escape sequence that expresses any character by its ASCII-code value.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] For example, the backslash can be expressed as either `\x5c` or `\134`, which specify the character code value in hexadecimal and octal notations, respectively.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Likewise, the lowercase *e* can be expressed as `\145` and the digit 7 as `\067`.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] A backslash immediately followed by a newline (which is necessarily outside of a string literal) does not mark an escape sequence.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Instead, it can be thought of as meaning "Disregard the newline": the C preprocessor joins the line with the subsequent line.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] In C and many related languages, the escape character is the backslash (`\`).
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] The single quotation mark character can be coded as `'\''` since `'''` is not valid.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] As a string literal is delimited by double-quotes (`"`) the content cannot contain a double-quote unless it is escaped (`"\""`) or via a sequence that specifies the code of the double-quote character (`\x22`).
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Alternatively, the following uses "\x" to indicate the subsequent two characters are hexadecimal digits; "22" being the hexadecimal ASCII value for double-quote.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] C, C++, Java, and Ruby allow the same two backslash escape styles.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] PostScript and rich text format (RTF) also use backslash escapes.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] The quoted-printable encoding uses the equals sign as an escape character.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] URL and URI use percent-encoding to quote characters with a special meaning, as for non-ASCII characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] The VT52 terminal used simple digraph commands like escape-A.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Without the escape character prefix, `A` simply meant the letter `A`, but as part of the escape sequence `escape-A`, it had a different meaning.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] It was not a straightforward control language encoded as substitution.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] The later VT100 terminal implemented the more sophisticated ANSI escape sequences standard (now ECMA-48) for functions such as controlling cursor movement, character set, and display enhancements.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] The HP 2640 series had perhaps the most elaborate escape sequences for block and character modes, programming keys and their soft labels, graphics vectors, and even saving data to tape or disk files.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] In Windows (and MS-DOS), a utility, ANSI.SYS, can be used to enable ANSI escape sequence support.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] In DOS via `$e` in the PROMPT command), and in 16-bit Windows via a command window.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the ANSI escape sequences are generally supported by the shell.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] The rise of GUI applications has reduced the use of escape sequences, yet the ability to provide full-screen, text-based applications is still available.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] A control sequence is a sequence of characters that changes the state of a computer peripheral instead of conveying the normal information that the characters represent.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] In an ANSI escape sequence, the escape sequence prefix, called control sequence introducer, can be either ASCII ESC (decimal 27) followed by `[` or CSI (decimal 155).
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Escape sequences in communications are commonly used when a computer and a peripheral have only a single channel through which to send information back and forth (so escape sequences are an example of in-band signaling).
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] They were common when most dumb terminals used ASCII with 7 data bits for communication, and sometimes would be used to switch to a different character set for "foreign" or graphics characters that would otherwise been restricted by the 128 codes available in 7 data bits.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Even relatively "dumb" terminals responded to some escape sequences, including the original mechanical Teletype printers (on which "glass Teletypes" or VDUs were based) responded to characters 27 and 31 to alternate between letters and figures modes.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Many computer keyboards have an Esc key (where *Esc* is short for *escape*) even though it is generally not used for entering an escape sequence.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] The vi text editor uses the key to exit from input mode.
[src:terminfo-termcap/escape-sequence] Some application use the key to cancel an operation or navigate up a level of a nested context.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] A termcap database can describe the capabilities of hundreds of different display terminals.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] This allows programs to have character-based display output, independent of the type of terminal.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] On-screen text editors such as vi and Emacs are examples of programs that may use termcap.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Other programs are listed in the Termcap category.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Access to the termcap database was usually provided by separate libraries, e.g.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Bill Joy wrote the first termcap library in 1978 for the Berkeley Unix operating system; it has since been ported to most Unix and Unix-like environments, even OS-9.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Joy's design was reportedly influenced by the design of the terminal data store in the earlier Incompatible Timesharing System.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Termcap databases consist of one or more descriptions of terminals.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Each description must contain the canonical name of the terminal.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] It may also contain one or more aliases for the name of the terminal.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The canonical name or aliases are the keys by which the library searches the termcap database.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The description contains one or more capabilities, which have conventional names.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The capabilities are typed: *boolean*, *numeric* and *string*.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The termcap library has no predetermined type for each capability name.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Applications which use termcap do expect specific types for the commonly used capabilities, and obtain the values of capabilities from the termcap database using library calls that return successfully only when the database contents matches the assumed type.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Termcap descriptions can be constructed by including the contents of one description in another, suppressing capabilities from the included description or overriding or adding capabilities.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] No matter what storage model is used, the termcap library constructs the terminal description from the requested description, including, suppressing or overriding at the time of the request.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Termcap data is stored as text, making it simple to modify.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The text can be retrieved by the termcap library from files or environment variables.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The **TERM** environment variable contains the terminal type name.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The **TERMCAP** environment variable may contain a termcap database.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] It is most often used to store a single termcap description, set by a terminal emulator to provide the terminal's characteristics to the shell and dependent programs.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The **TERMPATH** environment variable is supported by newer termcap implementations and defines a search path for termcap files.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The original (and most common) implementation of the termcap library retrieves data from a flat text file.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Searching a large termcap file, e.g., 500 kB, can be slow.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] To aid performance, a utility such as **reorder** is used to put the most frequently used entries near the beginning of the file.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] 4.4BSD based implementations of termcap store the terminal description in a hashed database (e.g., something like Berkeley DB version 1.85).
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] These store two types of records: aliases which point to the canonical entry, and the canonical entry itself.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The text of the termcap entry is stored literally.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Newer implementations of the termcap interface generally do not require the two-character name at the beginning of the entry.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Capability names are still two characters in all implementations.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The **tgetent** function used to read the terminal description uses a buffer whose size must be large enough for the data, and is assumed to be 1024 characters.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Newer implementations of the termcap interface may relax this constraint by allowing a null pointer in place of the fixed buffer, or by hiding the data which would not fit, e.g., via the **ZZ** capability in NetBSD termcap.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The terminfo library interface also emulates the termcap interface, and does not actually use the fixed-size buffer.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] The terminfo library's emulation of termcap allows multiple other entries to be included without restricting the position.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] A few other newer implementations of the termcap library may also provide this ability, though it is not well documented.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] A special capability, the "hz" capability, was defined specifically to support the Hazeltine 1500 terminal, which had the unfortunate characteristic of using the ASCII tilde character ('~') as a control sequence introducer.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Additionally, attribute markers (such as start and end of underlining) themselves took up space on the screen.
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Comments in the database source code often referred to this as "Hazeltine braindamage".
[src:terminfo-termcap/termcap] Since the Hazeltine 1500 was a widely used terminal in the late 1970s, it was important for applications to be able to deal with its limitations.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] A **terminal emulator**, or **terminal application**, is a computer program that emulates a video terminal within another display architecture.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Though typically synonymous with a shell or text terminal, the term *terminal* covers all remote terminals, including graphical interfaces.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] A terminal emulator inside a graphical user interface is often called a **terminal window**.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] A terminal window allows the user access to a text terminal and all its applications such as command-line interfaces (CLI) and text user interface (TUI) applications.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] These may be running either on the same machine or on a different one via telnet, ssh, dial-up, or over a direct serial connection.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] On Unix-like operating systems, it is common to have one or more terminal windows connected to the local machine.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Terminals usually support a set of escape sequences for controlling color, cursor position, etc.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Examples include the family of terminal control sequence standards that includes ECMA-48, ANSI X3.64, and ISO/IEC 6429.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] In the early days of computing, with the advent of interactive computing, the prevailing model involved a central computer connected to multiple terminals.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] This configuration, known as the centralized or mainframe model, featured a powerful central computer that performed all the processing tasks, while terminals served as input/output devices for users to interact with the system.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] These systems were initially character based.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] A character-oriented terminal is a type of computer terminal that communicates with its host one character at a time, as opposed to a block-oriented terminal that communicates in blocks of data.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] It is the most common type of data terminal, because it is easy to implement and program.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Connection to the mainframe computer or terminal server is achieved via RS-232 serial links, Ethernet or other proprietary protocols.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Character-oriented terminals can be "dumb" or "smart".
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Dumb terminals are those that can interpret a limited number of control codes (CR, LF, etc.) but do not have the ability to process special escape sequences that perform functions such as clearing a line, clearing the screen, or controlling cursor position.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] In this context dumb terminals are sometimes dubbed *glass Teletypes*, for they essentially have the same limited functionality as does a mechanical Teletype.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] This type of dumb terminal is still supported on modern Unix-like systems by setting the environment variable `TERM` to `dumb`.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Smart or intelligent terminals are those that also have the ability to process escape sequences, in particular the VT52, VT100 or ANSI escape sequences.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] When personal computers became ubiquitous in the 1980s, they offered the option of running software on the user's personal computer, providing an opportunity to replace the expensive and space consuming hardware terminals with something that had additional functions.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Immediately software became available, that could emulate the functions of the hardware terminals on a PC.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Examples of such software for DOS were Telix or Telemate, which was published in 1988 and could emulate a DEC VT102 terminal.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Workstations, usually running versions of Unix, also became common in the 1980s.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Unix systems usually provided access to the command line with locally-attached or dial-up terminals.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Unix workstations were designed to be used primarily through a graphical user interface (GUI); to provide access to the command line, the GUI included terminal emulator applications that behaved like locally-attached terminals.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Through the success of Linux on servers, especially running on data centers and cloud servers, the necessity of accessing remote computers through character-based terminal emulators remains.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators, such as xterm, implement additional features not present in the emulated terminal.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Additionally, programs have been developed to emulate assorted system console "terminals" such as the Sun workstation console and the Linux console.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Finally, some emulators simply refer to a set of standards, such as the standards for ANSI escape codes.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Such programs are available on many platforms, including DOS, Unix-like systems including Linux and macOS, Windows, and embedded operating systems found in cellphones and industrial hardware.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] In the past, Unix and Unix-like systems used serial port devices such as RS-232 ports, and provided `/dev/*` device files for them.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] With terminal emulators these device files are themselves emulated by a pair of pseudoterminal devices.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] These in turn emulate a physical port/connection to the host computing endpoint – hardware provided by operating system APIs, or software such as rlogin, telnet or SSH, among others.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] In Linux systems, for example, these would be `/dev/ptyp0` (for the master side) and `/dev/ttyp0` (for the slave side) pseudoterminal devices respectively.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] There are also special virtual console files like `/dev/console`.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] In text mode, writing to the file displays text on the virtual console and reading from the file returns text the user writes to the virtual console.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] As with other text terminals, there are also special escape sequences, control characters and functions that a program can use, most easily via a library such as *ncurses*.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] For more complex operations, the programs can use console and terminal special *ioctl* system calls.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] One can compare devices using the patterns vcs ("virtual console screen") and vcsa ("virtual console screen with attributes") such as `/dev/vcs1` and `/dev/vcsa1`.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Some terminal emulators also include escape sequences for configuring the behavior of the terminal to facilitate good interoperation between the terminal and programs running inside of it, for example to configure paste bracketing.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] The virtual consoles can be configured in the file `/etc/inittab` read by *init*—typically it starts the text mode login process *getty* for several virtual consoles.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] X Window System can be configured in `/etc/inittab` or by an X display manager.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] A number of Linux distributions use systemd instead of init, which also allows virtual console configuration.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement a local echo function, which may erroneously be named "half-duplex", or still slightly incorrectly "echoplex" (which is formally an error detection mechanism rather than an input display option).
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators may implement local editing, also known as "line-at-a-time mode".
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] This is also mistakenly referred to as "half-duplex".
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] In this mode, the terminal emulator only sends complete lines of input to the host system.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] The user enters and edits a line, but it is held locally within the terminal emulator as it is being edited.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] It is not transmitted until the user signals its completion, usually with the ↵ Enter key on the keyboard or a "send" button of some sort in the user interface.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] At that point, the entire line is transmitted.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Line-at-a-time mode implies local echo, since otherwise the user will not be able to see the line as it is being edited and constructed.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] However, line-at-a-time mode is independent of echo mode and does not *require* local echo.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] When entering a password, for example, line-at-a-time entry with local editing is possible, but local echo is turned off (otherwise the password would be displayed).
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] The complexities of line-at-a-time mode are exemplified by the line-at-a-time mode option in the telnet protocol.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] To implement it correctly, the *Network Virtual Terminal* implementation provided by the terminal emulator program must be capable of recognizing and properly dealing with "interrupt" and "abort" events that arrive in the middle of locally editing a line.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] In asynchronous terminals data can flow in any direction at any time.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] In **synchronous terminals** a protocol controls who may send data when.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] IBM 3270-based terminals used with IBM mainframe computers are an example of **synchronous terminals**.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] They operate in an essentially "screen-at-a-time" mode (also known as block mode).
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Users can make numerous changes to a page, before submitting the updated screen to the remote machine as a single action.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Terminal emulators that simulate the 3270 protocol are available for most operating systems, for use both by those administering systems such as the z9, as well as those using the corresponding applications such as CICS.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Other examples of synchronous terminals include the IBM 5250, ICL 7561, Honeywell Bull VIP7800 and Hewlett-Packard 700/92.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles, also called virtual terminals, are emulated text terminals, using the keyboard and monitor of a personal computer or workstation.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] The word "text" is key since virtual consoles are not GUI terminals and they do not run inside a graphical interface.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] Virtual consoles are found on most Unix-like systems.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminal-emulator] They are primarily used to access and interact with servers, without using a graphical desktop environment.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] Terminfo was included with UNIX System V Release 2 and soon became the preferred form of terminal descriptions in System V, rather than termcap (which BSD continued to use).
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] This was imitated in pcurses in 1982–1984 by Pavel Curtis, and was available on other UNIX implementations, adapting or incorporating fixes from Mary Horton.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] For more information, refer to the posting on the `comp.sources.unix` newsgroup from December 1986.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] A terminfo database can describe the capabilities of hundreds of different display terminals.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] This allows external programs to be able to have character-based display output, independent of the type of terminal.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] Terminfo databases consist of one or more descriptions of terminals.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] The canonical name or aliases are the keys by which the library searches the terminfo database.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] The terminfo library has predetermined types for each capability name.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] Applications which use terminfo know the types for the respective capabilities, and obtain the values of capabilities from the terminfo database using library calls that return successfully only when the capability name corresponds to one of the predefined typed capabilities.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] Like termcap, some of the *string* capabilities represent escape sequences which may be sent to the host by pressing special keys on the keyboard.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] Other capabilities represent strings that may be sent by an application to the terminal.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] In the latter case, the terminfo library functions (as does a termcap library) for substituting application parameters into the string which is sent.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] These functions provide a stack-based expression parser, which is primarily used to help minimize the number of characters sent for control sequences which have optional parameters such as SGR (Select Graphic Rendition).
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] In contrast, termcap libraries provide a limited set of operations which are useful for most terminals.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] Terminfo descriptions can be constructed by including the contents of one description in another, suppressing capabilities from the included description or overriding or adding capabilities.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] No matter what storage model is used, the terminfo library returns the terminal description from the requested description, using data which is compiled using a standalone tool (e.g., **tic**).
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] Terminfo data is stored as a binary file, making it less simple to modify than termcap.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] The data can be retrieved by the terminfo library from the files where it is stored.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] The data itself is organized as tables for the Boolean, numeric and string capabilities, respectively.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] This is the scheme devised by Mary Horton, and except for some differences regarding the available names is used in most terminfo implementations.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] X/Open does not specify the format of the compiled terminal description.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] In fact, it does not even mention the common **tic** or **infocmp** utilities.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] Because the compiled terminfo entries do not contain metadata identifying the indices within the tables to which each capability is assigned, they are not necessarily compatible between implementations.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] However, since most implementations use the same overall table structure (including sizes of header and data items), it is possible to automatically construct customized terminfo libraries which can read data for a given implementation.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] For example, ncurses can be built to match the terminfo data for several other implementations.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] The original (and most common) implementation of the terminfo library retrieves data from a directory hierarchy.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] By using the first character of the name of the terminal description as one component of the pathname, and the name of the terminal description as the name of the file to retrieve, the terminfo library usually outperforms searching a large termcap file.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] Some implementations of terminfo store the terminal description in a hashed database (e.g., something like Berkeley DB version 1.85).
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] These store two types of records: aliases which point to the canonical entry, and the canonical entry itself, which contains the data for the terminal capabilities.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] The Open Group documents the limits for terminfo (minimum guaranteed values), which apply only to the source file.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] The 14-character limit addresses very old filesystems which could represent filenames no longer than that.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] While those filesystems are generally obsolete, these limits were as documented from the late 1980s, and unreviewed since then.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] The 32,767 limit is for positive values in a signed two's complement 16-bit value.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] A terminfo entry may use negative numbers to represent cancelled or absent values.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] Unlike termcap, terminfo has both a source and compiled representation.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] The limits for the compiled representation are unspecified.
[src:terminfo-termcap/terminfo] However, most implementations note in their documentation for **tic** (terminal information compiler) that compiled entries cannot exceed 4,096 bytes in size.
